Save Lakshadweep

Agatti Island is a beautiful tropical paradise in Lakshadweep. Here's a possible plan for your trip from Bangalore:

Getting there:

Option 1: Fly directly from Kempegowda International Airport (BLR) in Bangalore to Agatti Airport (AGX). Several airlines offer direct flights, including Air India Express, Air India, and Akasa Air. The flight time is around 1 hour 30 minutes. Prices can range from â‚¹7,000 to â‚¹20,000 depending on the time of year and booking time.
Option 2: Fly from Bangalore to Cochin International Airport (COK) in Kerala and then take a connecting flight or ferry to Agatti Island. This can be a cheaper option, but it takes longer (around 4-5 hours). Ferry services operate only during the tourist season (October to May).
Permits and Visas:

Since Agatti falls under the Lakshadweep archipelago, Indian citizens require a special permit to visit. You can apply for the permit online through the official website of the Lakshadweep Tourism Department https://lakshadweep.gov.in/.
Foreign tourists require both a permit and a valid Indian visa.
Accommodation:

Agatti offers several options for accommodation, from budget guesthouses to luxurious resorts. Some popular choices include Agatti Island Beach Resort, Sinbad Beach Resort, and Surya Lagoon Maldives. Book your stay in advance, especially during peak season.
Activities:

Agatti is known for its stunning beaches, crystal-clear waters, and vibrant coral reefs. You can enjoy swimming, snorkeling, scuba diving, kayaking, and stand-up paddleboarding.
You can also visit the island's lighthouse, explore the local villages, and learn about the Lakshadweep culture.
Take a boat trip to nearby islands like Bangaram and Thinnakara for a change of scenery.
Travel duration:

Typically, 3-4 days is enough to experience the highlights of Agatti Island. However, if you want to relax and take things slow, you can stay longer.
Other things to keep in mind:

The best time to visit Agatti is during the dry season (October to May) when the weather is pleasant and the skies are clear.
Pack light and breathable clothing. Sunscreen, a hat, and sunglasses are essential.
Carry enough cash as ATMs are limited on the island.
Respect the local culture and customs.
Optional extensions:

After Agatti, you can consider visiting other islands in Lakshadweep like Bangaram or Kavaratti, each offering unique experiences.
You can also fly back to Bangalore directly from Agatti or via Cochin.

I had the opportunity to visit Lakshadweep islands in 2014...thanks to my brother who is a UT civil services officer and was posted there...made lifetime memories in Bangaram island...where there were barely 10-12 persons... I always imagined spending time on a secluded island enjoying solitude...the water is emerald blue and so clear that we could watch the fishes and corals below...went snorkelling in Bangaram and it was a lifetime experience which I cherish till today...rode a speed vessel, luxury speed boat from Agari to Bangaram...got the opportunity to ride a helicopter from Kavaratti to Kichi on my way back and that was another precious memory...I always felt that Lakshadweep islands have  tremendous tourism potential... though at that time there were a few hiccups while traveling from one island to another...I heard that new developments were going on for the past couple of years...would love to visit the newly developed island again

The untapped potential in the northeast is immense, yet the government has not made significant strides in improving infrastructure, public transport, or road conditions. It's disheartening when I compare China's advancements with India's shortcomings, especially in infrastructure development. China has efficiently connected its mainland to regions like Tibet through high-speed bullet trains, a feat that remains elusive for us in 2024. The lack of such connectivity hampers the growth of the northeast, which holds the potential for a thriving tourist industry comparable to destinations like the Maldives. Unfortunately, our political landscape often hinders progress, and we tend to react only when faced with crises, rather than learning from successful models. Despite the challenges, I remain hopeful for positive changes in the future.

Beautiful video.
This is a place about which very few people in India know about, or take interest in.

To travel to a place where you know no one, where communication is mostly by sign language , and yet to feel at home there, says a lot about your enquiring nature.

Though the Khasi people are cut off from the rest of India, and have to live in very harsh climatic conditions, they, like you   have a very positive way of looking at life, always smiling,  friendly in their own way.

 Having very few visitors in this remote village makes them a little reserved, shy , wary and so they keep their distance from outsiders.

 But they are happy. The contentment on their faces is so obvious.

Perhaps tourism has not spoilt the peace  beauty and tranquility of this place , that it has a dream like quality, enhanced by the constant rain, heavy mist and rolling fog, which hides this enchanting  place from the rest of India.
Thank you for the effort you took to go to this  Shangri-la. and for sharing your memories of this abode of clouds.
